<learningObject editorVersion="3" targetFolder="Nottingham" name="&lt;p style=&quot;margin-bottom:0.35cm&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background:transparent&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;line-height:115%&quot;&gt;&lt;font face=&quot;Calibri, serif&quot;&gt;&lt;font size=&quot;2&quot;&gt;&lt;font style=&quot;font-size: 11pt&quot;&gt;Preparing to Shovel Snow: Safety, Comfort, Efficiency&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;" language="en-GB" navigation="Historic" textSize="14" theme="django" displayMode="fill window" responsive="true" progressBar="pBar" homePage="PG1606332074072" background="Select an Image" backgroundopacity="30" backgroundDark="0" backgroundGrey="true"><title linkID="PG1606332074072" name="Welcome" size="70"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent"><strong style="font-weight:bold"><font size="7"><font style="font-size: 44pt">How to shovel snow safety</font></font></strong><font size="7"><font style="font-size: 44pt"> </font></font></span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></title><text linkID="PG1606332553020" name="Introduction&amp;nbsp;"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt">Snow shoveling isn&#39;t fun, but it&#39;s often unavoidable. In areas where snow is no stranger, it&#39;s ill-advised to allow even the most meager snowfall to go unshoveled in your driveway, lest it later melt and refreeze. The resulting sheet of ice becomes a slipping hazard.</font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606332718421" name="Preparing to Shovel Snow: Safety, Comfort, Efficiency"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">As for any yard maintenance job, priority #1 in snow shoveling is safety, followed closely by comfort and efficiency. Consider doing the following before you even step outside:</span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606332886134" name="Step 1" narration="Select an Audio File" playNarration="false" narrationNavigate="false"><![CDATA[<p><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">Stretch your muscles to prevent injury. </span></font></font></font></span></span></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<div class="embeddedContent oembed-provider- oembed-provider-youtube" data-align="center" data-maxheight="315" data-maxwidth="560" data-oembed="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=COeO0zydlOo&amp;feature=emb_logo&amp;ab_channel=AdvocateHealthCare" data-oembed_provider="youtube" data-resizetype="responsive" data-title="How to stretch" style="text-align: center;"><iframe allowfullscreen="true" allowscriptaccess="always" frameborder="0" height="315" scrolling="no" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/COeO0zydlOo?wmode=transparent&amp;feature=emb_logo&amp;ab_channel=AdvocateHealthCare&amp;jqoemcache=3bJcF" title="How to stretch" width="383.5959885386819"></iframe></div>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606333273550" name="Step 2" narration="Select an Audio File" playNarration="false" narrationNavigate="false"><![CDATA[<p><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt">Dress in layers to stay warm. </font></font></font></span></span></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606395758210" name="Step 3"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">Vow to take breaks: continuous snow shoveling can be hazardous to the health of those in not-such-great shape.&nbsp;</span> </font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606395946979" name="Step 4"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt">&quot;Wax&quot; your shovel blade, making it slippery and thereby preventing snow from sticking to it. Although candle wax, floor wax, or car wax may be used, Pam spray works fine, too.</font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><title linkID="PG1606396182406" name="Section 2" size="30"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="7"><font style="font-size: 48pt">Staying Safe and Proper Shoveling Technique&nbsp;</font></font></font></span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></title><text linkID="PG1606396350148" name="Step 1"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">The stretching you had you do above is just step #1 in snow shoveling the safe way. Once you step outside and start wielding your shovel, remember the following: </span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606396561109" name="Step 2"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt">Bend your knees and lift with your legs.</font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606396714764" name="Step 3"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">As you lift the snow, keep the shovel blade close to you, to reduce back strain.</span> </font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606396834379" name="Step 4"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">Switch off between snow shoveling right-handed and left-handed, so that you&#39;re working different muscles. </span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606396960329" name="Step 5"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">Periodically change your grip on the hand holding the bar (palm under vs. palm over).</span> </font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606397091241" name="Step 6"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">When the snowfall is heavy (1 foot in depth, let&#39;s say), don&#39;t try to clean right down to the ground with a single scoop. Instead, skim the top 6 inches off, then scoop up the bottom 6 inches. Otherwise, you could be hurting yourself by lifting too much</span> </font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><title linkID="PG1606397172223" name="Section 3" size="30"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="7"><font style="font-size: 48pt"><span style="background:transparent">Snow Shoveling Tips for Those Who Park in the Driveway</span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></title><text linkID="PG1606397425316" name="Step 1"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">Save yourself some time and trouble by clearing a path to the driver&#39;s door of your car first. Once inside, start your car and turn on the defrosting mechanisms (front and back). Crank the heat full-blast, even though only cold air will come out initially (it will have a chance to warm up while you&#39;re snow shoveling). </span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606397651357" name="Step 2"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">By defrosting your windows, you make it easier to clean the snow (and ice) off them. Besides, when you&#39;re done snow shoveling, don&#39;t you want a nice warm car to get into? </span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606397811288" name="Step 3"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">By clearing a path to your car first, you avoid trampling down snow on the way. Trampled snow has to be removed later, anyway, and it&#39;s tougher to remove than unpacked snow. </span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><title linkID="PG1606397930511" name="Section 4" size="30"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font size="7"><font style="font-size: 48pt"><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><span style="background:transparent">Have a Plan Before You Start Shoveling</span></font><font face="Calibri, serif"> </font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></title><text linkID="PG1606398122843" name="Step 1"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Calibri, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">Don&#39;t fuss about the rest of the snow around the car just yet. More snow will accumulate there when you clean the car, so you might as well wait till then to clean up around the perimeter of the car.</span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606398385540" name="Step 2"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">Hold off on snow shoveling (with any degree of thoroughness) where your driveway meets the street. As plows go by, they&#39;ll be barricading that area with more snow. Save this area till you&#39;re ready to pull out with your car, or till after you&#39;ve rested up<font face="Calibri, serif"> </font></span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606398541210" name="Step 3"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">If you can afford the luxury of clearing a driveway in stages, that&#39;s the way to go. If the storm&#39;s over, divide the workload into sections; if the storm&#39;s still in progress, make a preliminary sweep, then go back after the storm</span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text><text linkID="PG1606413287032" name="End of the lesson"><![CDATA[<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent"><font face="Calibri, serif">Remember Safety, Comfort,&nbsp; and Efficiency.</font></span></font></font></font></span></span></p>

<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">Defrost your car windows.</span></font></font></font></span></span></p>

<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">Have a Plan Before You Start Shoveling.</span></font></font></font></span></span></p>

<p style="margin-bottom:0.35cm"><span style="background:transparent"><span style="line-height:115%"><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font size="5"><font style="font-size: 18pt"><span style="background:transparent">Take breaks.</span></font></font></font></span></span></p>
]]></text></learningObject>
